br.com.summa.sol.util

Class Chains

  • java.lang.Object
    • br.com.summa.sol.util.Chains

  • public final class Chains
extends Object
    Convenience class to build a (delimiter separated) string from a provided sequence of elements.

    It's somewhat similar to String.join(...) and StringJoiner from Java 1.8, except it can be used with arbitrary data types, not just CharSequence.
    Author:
    Einar Saukas

    • Method Detail

      • join

        @SafeVarargs
public static <T> String join(CharSequence delimiter,
                                            T... elems)
        Returns a string containing the provided sequence of elements (separated by the provided delimiter).

        It's somewhat similar to String.join(CharSequence delimiter, CharSequence... elems) from Java 1.8, except it accepts all data types, not just CharSequence.

        Typical usage: 
        
 String str1 = Chains.join(" - ", 0, 1, 1, 2, 3, 5, 8, 13);
 // returns "0 - 1 - 1 - 2 - 3 - 5 - 8 - 13"

 String str2 = Chains.join(".", "", "a", "", "", "b", null, "c", "");
 // returns ".a...b.null.c."
        Type Parameters:
        T - Type of elements
        Parameters:
        delimiter - Provided delimiter
        elems - Sequence of elements
        Returns:
        A string containing the provided sequence of elements (separated by the provided delimiter)

      • traverse

        public static String traverse(CharSequence delimiter,
                              Iterable<?> obj)
        Returns a String containing elements from the provided iterable object (separated by the provided delimiter).

        It's somewhat similar to String.join(CharSequence delimiter, Iterable elems) from Java 1.8, except it accepts all data types, not just CharSequence.

        Typical usage: 
        
 List<Integer> list = Arrays.asList(1,2,3,4,5);
 String str = Chains.traverse(" - ", list);
 // returns "1 - 2 - 3 - 4 - 5"
        Notice it also works for other collections: 
        
 Map<String, Object> map = new LinkedHashMap<String, Object>();
 map.put("a", 1);
 map.put("b", 2);
 map.put("c", 3);
 ...
 String keys = Chains.traverse("-", map.keySet());
 // returns "a-b-c"

 String vals = Chains.traverse("-", map.values());
 // returns "1-2-3"

 String both = Chains.traverse(" AND ", map.entrySet());
 // returns "a=1 AND b=2 AND c=3"
        Parameters:
        delimiter - Provided delimiter
        obj - Iterable object
        Returns:
        A String containing elements from the provided iterable object (separated by the provided delimiter)

      • traverse

        public static String traverse(CharSequence delimiter,
                              Iterator<?> it)
        Returns a string containing elements from the provided iterator (separated by the provided delimiter)).

        It's somewhat similar to String.join(CharSequence delimiter, Iterable elems) from Java 1.8, except it accepts all data types, not just CharSequence.

        Typical usage: 
        
 LinkedList list = new LinkedList(Arrays.asList('a', 'b', 'c'));
 String str = Chains.traverse(" - ", list.descendingIterator());
 // returns "c - b - a"
        Parameters:
        delimiter - Provided delimiter
        it - Iterator
        Returns:
        A String containing elements from the provided iterator (separated by the provided delimiter)

      • merge

        public static String merge(CharSequence delimiter,
                           CharSequence... elems)
        Returns a string containing the provided sequence of elements, separated by the provided delimiter), but skipping empty (or null) strings. So it can be used to combine results produced by multiple Chains.

        Typical usage: 
        
 String str1 = Chains.traverse("-", list1);
 String str2 = Chains.traverse("-", list2);
 String str = Chains.merge(".", str1, str2);
        Parameters:
        delimiter - Provided delimiter
        elems - Sequence of elements
        Returns:
        A string containing the provided sequence of elements, separated by the provided delimiter), but skipping empty (or null) strings
